lled without job control enabled.\n\n**Solution:**\nRemove `%{suse_update_config -f}` from your `%build` section entirely. Modern openSUSE packaging standards rely on `%configure`, which automatically and safely updates `config.status` without triggering shell job control issues. If you have already run `%configure` earlier in `%build`, this line is redundant and can be deleted safely. \n\nIf an explicit update is strictly required after a later stage, wrap it in a subshell that temporarily enables job control:\n```spec\n+ (set -m; %{suse_update_config -f})\n```\nHowever, per openSUSE conventions, removal is the preferred fix. Save the spec and rebuild.\n-----------------------------\n\n\n--- OLLAMA ERROR ANALYSIS (after deep investigation) ---\n**Error Analysis:**\nThe build fails with `fg: no job control` because rpmbuild disables shell job control (`set +m`) in non-interactive `%build` scripts for security and reproducibility. The macro `%{suse_update_config -f}` invokes a helper (`generic-update-config`/`config_status`) that attempts to use `fg` (foreground a background process). Bash aborts when `fg` is called without job control enabled.\n\n**Solution:**\nRemove `%{suse_update_config -f}` from your `%build` section entirely. Modern openSUSE packaging standards rely on `%configure`, which automatically and safely updates `config.status` without triggering shell job control issues. If you have already run `%configure` earlier in `%build`, this line is redundant and can be deleted safely. \n\nIf an explicit update is strictly required after a later stage, wrap it in a subshell that temporarily enables job control:\n```spec\n+ (set -m; %{suse_update_config -f})\n```\nHowever, per openSUSE conventions, removal is the preferred fix. Save the spec and rebuild.\n-----------------------------\n\n[FIX MODE] Applying suggested changes via tool calls...\n[TOOL] read_file: gawk.spec\n[FIX] read_file: gawk.spec (95 lines)\n[TOOL] --- Diff for /home/adrian/opencode/pbuild-ai